generated_text:
 Let's denote the flipping of the coins as events A1, A2, A3, and A4, with A_i representing the event of the ith coin landing on heads. Since all coins are fair, we have P(A_i) = 1/2 for all i. 
We can then consider the following events for the coins landing on heads or tails: 
1. A1 U A2 U A3 U A4 represents the event that all four coins land on heads. 
2. A1 U A2 U A3 U A4 represents the event that all four coins land on tails.

By the principle of inclusion-exclusion for three events, we have: 
\begin{align*}
P(A1 U A2 U A3 U A4) &= P(A1) + P(A2) + P(A3) + P(A4) \\
&- P(A1 \cap A2) - P(A1 \cap A3) - P(A1 \cap A4) \\
&- P(A2 \cap A3) - P(A2 \cap A4) - P(A3 \cap A4) \\
&+ P(A1 \cap A2 \cap A3) + P(A1 \cap A2 \cap A4) \\
&+ P(A1 \cap A3 \cap A4) + P(A2 \cap A3 \cap A4) \\
&- P(A1 \cap A2 \cap A3 \cap A4)
\end{align*}
However, since the events are independent, we can simplify this to:
\begin{align*}
P(A1 U A2 U A3 U A4) &= 4 \cdot P(A1) \\
&= 4 \cdot \frac{1}{2} \\
&= \frac{4}{2} \\
&= \boxed{1}
\end{align*}
But this represents the probability of the coins all landing on the same side, which is not what we want. We need to find the probability of all four landing on heads or all four landing on tails, not just the same side. 
Let B be the event that all four coins land on heads and T be the event that all four coins land on tails. 
B and T are mutually exclusive, so:
\begin{align*}
P(B U T) &= P(B) + P(T) \\
&= P(B) + P(B')
\end{align*}
where B' is the event that all four coins land on tails.
Since all four coins are fair and independent, we have:
\begin{align*}
P(B) &= \left(\frac{1}{2}\right)^4 \\
&= \frac{1}{16} \\
P(B') &= \left(\frac{1}{2}\right)^4 \\
&= \frac{1}{16}
\end{align*}
Therefore, the probability that all four coins will be heads or all four will be tails is:
\begin{align*}
P(B U T) &= \frac{1}{16} + \frac{1}{16} \\
&= \boxed{\frac{2}{16}} \\
&= \boxed{\frac{1}{8}}
\end{align*}

